<!DOCTYPE intro
  SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<intro xmlns="Unit"
       xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
       xsi:schemaLocation="Unit file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Unit.xsd">
   <block>
      <block.body>
         <para>
            <para.body>In this chapter we introduce two fundamental operations on vectors, and learn how to use them:</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
		          <li>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The first operation is quite intuitive: the length or norm of a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is just the length of any arrow representing <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>. If <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}= (x_1,\dots, x_n)</latex>
                     </math>, then the norm of <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> is</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Abs{\Vect{x}}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>:=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\sqrt{ x_{1}^{2} + \cdots + x_{n}^{2} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The norm operation has 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>algebraic properties</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="theo_NormAlgebraicProperties"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>See the statement of the algebraic properties of the norm operation.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>
				which match what one would expect of ‘length of a vector’.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </li>
		          <li>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The second operation is the ‘dot product’. It receives as input two vectors <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>. It delivers a 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>number, denoted <math>
                              <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                           </math>
                        </hot>
                        <companion>
                           <definition.ref definitionID="Def_DotProduct"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>See how the dot product is computed.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>. The way the dot product is 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>computed</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <definition.ref definitionID="Def_DotProduct"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>See how the dot product is computed.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate> conveys nothing of its meaning. It is, therefore, perhaps a bit surprising, that the dot product is a very useful and versatile operation.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This usefulness and versatility comes from its
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>geometric properties</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Theo_DotProductNormGeometricProperties"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Preview the geometric properties of the dot product.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>. They tell us about the relationship between norm and dot product: <math>
                        <latex>\Abs{ \Vect{x} }^2 = \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                     </math>, and the angle between two vectors. In particular, we obtain a very convenient test for when two vectors are perpendicular.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </li>
		          <li>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We use the dot product to construct the 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>orthogonal projection of a vector onto a line</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <unit.ref unitId="Illu_ProjectionVectorLine"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>An illustration of the orthogonal projection of a vector onto a line</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </li>
		          <li>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>We use the dot product to describe 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>hyperspaces</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <unit.ref unitId="Illu_HyperSpace"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>An illustration of a hyperspace in <math>
                                       <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                    </math> and in <math>
                                       <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>
				and 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>hyperplanes</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <unit.ref unitId="Illustr_Hyperplane"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>An illustration of a hyperplane in <math>
                                       <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                                    </math> and in <math>
                                       <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>
				in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math>. It enables us further to compute the
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>distance</hot>
                        <companion>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_DistancePointHyperplane"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>See the formula to compute the distance of a point from a hyperplane.</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </companion>
                     </subordinate>
				of an arbitrary point in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                     </math> from a given hyperplane.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </li>
	        </ol>
      </block.body>
   </block>
</intro>
